		<p>Most of the time things work just fine. We see stuff, the brain makes sense out of it; how it moves and changes over time. Occasionally, nothing is there, neither does it move. A video that you watch on YouTube isn't real. It's just millions of tiny light bulbs changing color as dictated by the computer. Everything is static, except for the intensity of light and the wavelength for each pixel.</p>
		<blockquote><p>We think something is in motion when it's moving along the vertical or horisontal axis. It could swing like a pendulum or it could move in a single direction.</p></blockquote>
		<p>We think something is in motion when it changes ten times per second or faster. What happens to it within each one of those moments is crucial as it adds to our idea of where it moves or how it changes.</p>
